Fr. de Young on "Lord of Spirits" talked about it, but back in the time of Second Temple Judaism there was a tradition that there was going to be a second, priestly Moshiach from the tribe of Levi (as opposed to the Davidic royal one) who is the more important one of the two.

When St. John the Baptist sends his disciple to ask Christ if they are to expect "another one" in Matthew 11, he is referring to this, asking if there will be a second messiah. There is also celestial symbolism like comparing the priestly messiah to the sun and royal to the moon.

Before the Levitical priesthood of Aaron was established, Jewish religion was very similar to what Galkovsky and Evola note about Roman religion, priesthood is a function and not a vocation, just something the Paterfamilias does, head of household offering sacrifices and stuff...
I guess in a minor sense every man is the priest in his household... E.g. when it comes to burning frankincense or leading in prayer etc...

Early Olympic games in 19th, 20t century resemble the period of Roman Republicanism, lack of organization acting as a fecund ground for spontaneous acts of individual heroism manifesting in unlikely triumphs, later to give way to brutal, machinelike efficiency and optimization...
